description:
Feathers found below tree frequented by bald eagle. Juvenile gull. Primary feather is 26.5 cm (just under 10.5 inches) and tail feathers are 15 cm (just under 6 inches) long. Tail feathers are similar to these juvenile ring-billed gull tail feathers in the feather atlas. Good photos of juvenile tail feathers of other Larus species are hard to find, even online, but Sibley notes the ‘whitish rump and tail base’ on the juvenile ring-billed gull which is absent in other gulls common to the North Okanagan, so ring-billed gull seems the most likely candidate. 
https://www.fws.gov/lab/featheratlas/feather.php?Bird=RBGU_tail_imm4

description:
BC Parks employee in attendance recognised the deer fur appearance, being sheared rather than pulled, as characteristic of a cougar and not a bear.

From mountainlion.org
"...before eating any part of an ungulates body the mountain lion will meticulously pluck the hair, one mouthful after another, leaving a large pile of distinctively clumped fur."

From santacruzpumas.org
"Lions will nip the hair off of the body of a deer before they start chewing into it. The clumps of nipped hair are about 1” across – the distance between the lion’s canine teeth."
